lites and reveals the often neglected force of enthusiasm, and of emotions more generally, in shaping beliefs and in motivating actions. He provides the first detailed examinations of “divide and rule” as a strategy used on both sides of the Atlantic and of the rise and fall of collective action movements among the Americans. Elster also explains how the gradual undermining in America of the British imperial system took its toll on transatlantic relations and describes how state governments and the American Confederation made crucial institutional decisions that informed and constrained the making of the Constitution.Drawing on a wide range of historical sources and on theories of modern social science, Elster brings together two fields of scholarship in innovative and original ways. The result is a unique synthesis that yields new insights into some of the most important events in modern history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aUnited States-History-Colonial period, ca. 1600-1775. 0aUnited States-History-Confederation, 1783-1789. 0aUnited States-History-Revolution, 1775-1783. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  aAlbany Congress.  aAmerican Confederation.  aAmerican Constitution.  aAmerican Politics.  aAmerican Revolution.  aAmerican history.  aAnglo-American treaty.  aArticles of Confederation.  aBenjamin Franklin.  aBoard of Trade.  aBoston Massacre.  aBoston Port Act.  aBoston Port Bill.  aBoston Tea Party.  aBritish Army.  aBritish government.  aBritish-American Relations.  aCollective Action.  aDavid Ramsay.  aDivide and Rule.  aEdmund Burke.  aEmotions.  aFederalist Papers.  aFirst Continental Congress.  aHistorical Sociology.  aJames Madison.  aJeremy Bentham.  aJohn Adams.  aJohn Dickinson.  aMassachusetts.  aNew World.  aOliver Dic